\dfrac{d}{dx} \left( \dfrac{dy}{dx} \right) = \dfrac{2x}{u^2} = \dfrac1{u^2}\dfrac{du}{dx} \implies d \left( \dfrac{dy}{dx} \right) = \dfrac{du}{u^2} \implies \dfrac{dy}{dx} = - \dfrac1u + C
